ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the photothermal performance of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA, a NIR laser (808 nm, 2 W/cm2) was used to irradiate the solution with various concentrations (12.5, 25, 50, and 100 μg/mL) for 6 min, and the temperature variation was simultaneously recorded using an infrared thermal imaging camera. As shown in Fig. 2
                        a, the temperature of all CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA samples had an obvious increase with the irradiation time, and a more faster heating rate with the increased concentration of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA. Notably, the temperature of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA at concentrations of 100 μg/mL for CQDs and 18 μg/mL for ICG increased to 45.4 °C after 6 min of irradiation, which was significantly higher than pure CQDs (38.4 °C) and free ICG (38.7 °C) at the same concentrations, thus showing the synergistic photothermal effect of CQDs and ICG in CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA (
                           Figure S3
                        ). Meanwhile, this temperature was also above the threshold required to induce irreversible apoptosis of tumor cells (42 °C) and trigger CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA to release the encapsulated drug. The temperature changes of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA at different laser power densities were also recorded (
                           Figure S4
                        ), and the results showed that even at a power of 0.42 W/cm2, the temperature could rise by 8.6 °C. The photostability of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA was studied as depicted in Fig. 1c. After five consecutive on/off cycles, the maximum temperature rise of the CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA solution in each cycle was slightly lower than that of the preceding cycle. This was attributed to the decomposition of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA to release ICG molecules embedded in the bilayer membrane, while unprotected ICG molecules were easily bleached when exposed to light and heat [40]. The photothermal conversion efficiency (η) of CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA was determined using a previously described equation [32,33] and calculated to be 47.14 % (Fig. 2b), which was higher than previous studies such as Polypyrrole@Fe3O4 (η = 39.15 %) [41], Au nanorods (η = 21 %) [42], and conjugated-polymer nanoparticles (η = 34.7 %) [43], indicating superior photothermal conversion performance. Additionally, the CQDs/ICG/DOX@LPs-FA exhibited a localized heating in the center when exposed to NIR light irradiation as illustrated in Fig. 2d, Fig. 2e, Fig. 2f, and Fig. 2g. This highlights the specificity of photothermal therapy, where the therapeutic effect occurs only at the site of the lesion without damaging the surrounding cells.
